doc.ContractDescription: COLLABORATIVE RESEARCH: NRI-SMALL: LONG-RANGE PREDICTION OF NON-GEOMETRIC TERRAIN HAZARDS FOR RELIABLE PLANETARY ROVER TRAVERSE. NON-GEOMETRIC TERRAIN HAZARDS ARE MISSION-ENDERS FOR AUTONOMOUS GROUND VEHICLES ON EARTH AND BEYOND. SPIRIT WAS MIRED IN SOFT SOIL ON MARS; LUNOKHOD BECAME STUCK IN REGOLITH ON THE MOON. AUTONOMOUS GROUND VEHICLES MUST DETECT AND REACT TO OFF-NOMINAL CONDITIONS TO LIMIT RISK AND MAXIMIZE PERFORMANCE. WHILE VISUAL AND ACTIVE OPTICAL SENSORS (E.G., STEREO CAMERAS AND LIDAR) EXCEL AT SENSING GEOMETRIC OBSTACLES, THEY FAIL TO DETECT HAZARDS LIKE WEAK OR SLIPPERY TERRAIN. RECENT RESEARCH INTO SENSING OF NONGEOMETRIC TERRAIN PROPERTIES TAKES A DRIVE-BY-FEEL APPROACH, WHERE TERRAIN PROPERTIES ARE MEASURED BY DRIVING OVER THE TERRAIN AND COMPARING OBSERVED MOTION TO ACTUATION EFFORT. THE MEASUREMENTS ARE CORRELATED WITH TERRAIN APPEARANCE TO PREDICT UPCOMING HAZARDS. WHILE EFFECTIVE AT SHORT RANGE, THIS APPROACH IS INDIRECT AND CANNOT MEASURE TERRAIN PROPERTIES WITHOUT WHEEL-TERRAIN CONTACT. WE PROPOSE A NOVEL, TWO-PRONGED APPROACH INCORPORATING LONG-RANGE SENSING AND RECEDING HORIZON CONTROL TO ENSURE SAFE OPERATION DURING AUTONOMOUS PLANETARY TRAVERSE. THE PROPOSED APPROACH INVESTIGATES AND DEVELOPS DETECTION OF NON-GEOMETRIC HAZARDS WITH MULTIPLE SENSING MODES TO ASCERTAIN TERRAIN PROPERTIES AT RANGE. SELF-SUPERVISED LEARNING MAPS MULTI-MODE LONG-RANGE SENSOR DATA TO TERRAIN PROPERTIES MEASURED BY DIRECT-CONTACT INSTRUMENTS AND TO OBSERVED VEHICLE PERFORMANCE. RECEDING HORIZON CONTINGENCY PLANNING APPLIES LEARNED MODELS OF VEHICLE-TERRAIN INTERACTION TO MAINTAIN STABILITY AND SAFETY. THIS RESEARCH INVESTIGATES MULTIPLE SENSING MODES FOR SHORT AND LONG RANGE TERRAIN PROPERTY MEASUREMENT. THE PROPOSED SOFTWARE DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM INNOVATES LEARNING FOR TERRAIN CLASSIFICATION AND CONTROLS THE ROVER UNDER DYNAMIC CONSTRAINTS. THE PROGRAM CULMINATES WITH FIELD DEMONSTRATION OF THE DEVELOPED TECHNOLOGY.

doc.ContractDescription: A PAYLOAD IS PROPOSED TO DETECT COSMIC RAYS, HIGH-ENERGY PARTICLES OF ASTROPHYSICAL ORIGIN, IN THE ENERGY RANGE ~1-100 GEV. ENERGY DETERMINATION WILL BE FACILITATED BY A SIX-LAYER, SAMPLING CALORIMETER WITH A THICKNESS OF ~12.5 RADIATION LENGTHS. A SEGMENTED CHARGE DETECTOR WILL BE EMPLOYED TO DISTINGUISH PROTONS FROM HELIUM NUCLEI, THE TWO MOST ABUNDANT COSMIC RAYS TYPES, WHILE MINIMIZING CHARGE-MEASUREMENT CONTAMINATION FROM UPWARD-GOING SECONDARY PARTICLES DUE TO PRIMARY COSMIC-RAY INTERACTIONS IN THE CALORIMETER. THE PAYLOAD WILL BE CARRIED TO AN ALTITUDE OF 120,000 FT FOR A FLIGHT DURATION OF 6 HOURS VIA THE NEAR SPACE CORPORATIONS SMALL BALLOON SYSTEM. PAYLOAD DESIGN, CONSTRUCTION, INTEGRATION, AND LAUNCH WILL BE COMPLETED BY AN INTERDISCIPLINARY TEAM OF SCIENCE AND ENGINEERING UNDERGRADUATE STUDENTS WITH OVERSIGHT FROM TWO FACULTY ADVISORS.

doc.ContractDescription: IN CLOSE COLLABORATION WITH NASA/GFSC, THE PROPOSED RESEARCH SEEKS TO USE AN ENSEMBLE KALMAN FILTER (ENKF) TO ASSIMILATE FIELD CAMPAIGN AND OTHER SOURCES OF OBSERVATIONS DURING THE HS3 FIELD CAMPAIGN TO UNDERSTAND THE DYNAMICS AND PREDICTABILITY OF HURRICANE STRUCTURE AND INTENSITY CHANGES. SPECIAL EMPHASIS WILL BE ON THE TWO ONLY MAJOR HURRICANES THAT WERE SAMPLED DURING HS3, HURRICANE EDOUARD (2014) FROM INSTRUMENTS ABOARD THE NASA'S GLOBAL HAWK UNMANNED AERIAL SYSTEM (AV-6) AND HURRICANE GONZALO (2014) FROM INSTRUMENT ONBOARD OF MANNED AIRCRAFT WB-57. BOTH STORMS EXPERIENCED RAPID INTENSIFICATION SHORTLY AFTER GENESIS, ALONG WITH STRUCTURE AND INTENSITY CHANGES ACCOMPANYING AT LEAST PARTIAL EYEWALL REPLACEMENT CYCLES AROUND PEAK INTENSITY. BOTH STORMS WERE ALSO SAMPLED BY INSTRUMENTS ABOARD NOAA RECONNAISSANCE AIRCRAFTS THAT WILL COMPLEMENT THE HS5 OBSERVATIONS FOR BOTH ENKF ASSIMILATION AND VALIDATION.
